<section xml:id="sec-cubes-and-right-prisms" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Cubes and Right Prisms</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>First, we'll analyze shapes like cubes, boxes, and other <q>prisms</q>.</p>

    <image width="80%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Cube
            \begin{scope}[shift={(0,0)}, scale=0.7]
              \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (2,2) -- (0,2) -- cycle;
              \draw[thick] (0.7,2.7) -- (2.7,2.7) -- (2.7,0.7);
              \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (2.7,0.7);
              \draw[thick] (2,2) -- (2.7,2.7);
              \draw[thick] (0,2) -- (0.7,2.7);
              \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0.7,0.7) -- (2.7,0.7);
              \draw[dashed] (0.7,0.7) -- (0.7,2.7);
              \node[below] at (1.35,-0.3) {Cube};
            \end{scope}
            % Rectangular prism (box)
            \begin{scope}[shift={(4.5,0)}, scale=0.7]
              \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2.8,0) -- (2.8,1.5) -- (0,1.5) -- cycle;
              \draw[thick] (0.7,2.2) -- (3.5,2.2) -- (3.5,0.7);
              \draw[thick] (2.8,0) -- (3.5,0.7);
              \draw[thick] (2.8,1.5) -- (3.5,2.2);
              \draw[thick] (0,1.5) -- (0.7,2.2);
              \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0.7,0.7) -- (3.5,0.7);
              \draw[dashed] (0.7,0.7) -- (0.7,2.2);
              \node[below] at (1.75,-0.3) {Box (rectangular prism)};
            \end{scope}
            % Triangular prism
            \begin{scope}[shift={(10,0)}, scale=0.7]
              \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (1.3,0.9);
              \draw[dashed] (1.3,0.9) -- (0,0);
              \draw[thick] (0,2.3) -- (2,2.3) -- (1.3,3.2) -- cycle;
              \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,2.3);
              \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (2,2.3);
              \draw[thick] (1.3,0.9) -- (1.3,3.2);
              \node[below] at (1,-0.3) {Triangular prism};
            \end{scope}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

    <p>Notice that all of these shapes have 2 bases, that are connected by flat rectangular faces. This type of shape is called a <term>right prism</term>. The word <q>right</q> means the sides are perpendicular to the base (they are at right angles to the base).</p>
  </introduction>

  <!-- ============================== -->
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-cube">
    <title>Cube</title>

    <p>A <term>cube</term> is a right prism where all 6 faces are squares, which are all the same size. If the side length is <m>x</m>, then to get volume, multiply all 3 of the dimensions together.</p>

    <image width="35%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
          % Front face
          \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (2,2) -- (0,2) -- cycle;
          % Back face (visible edges)
          \draw[thick] (0.8,2.8) -- (2.8,2.8) -- (2.8,0.8);
          % Connecting edges
          \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (2.8,0.8);
          \draw[thick] (2,2) -- (2.8,2.8);
          \draw[thick] (0,2) -- (0.8,2.8);
          % Hidden edges
          \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0.8,0.8) -- (2.8,0.8);
          \draw[dashed] (0.8,0.8) -- (0.8,2.8);
          % Dimension arrows
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-0.3) -- (2,-0.3) node[midway, below] {$x$};
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-0.3,0) -- (-0.3,2) node[midway, left] {$x$};
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (2.15,-0.15) -- (2.95,0.65) node[midway, below right] {$x$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p>This gives <m>x \cdot x \cdot x</m> = <m>x^3</m>.</p>

    <p>The volume of a cube is,</p>
    <me>\boxed{V_{\text{cube}} = x^3 \quad x \rightarrow \text{side length}}</me>

    <exercise>
      <title>Volume of a Cube</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the volume of a cube with side length 4 cm.</p>
        <image width="25%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]
              \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (2,2) -- (0,2) -- cycle;
              \draw[thick] (0.7,2.7) -- (2.7,2.7) -- (2.7,0.7);
              \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (2.7,0.7);
              \draw[thick] (2,2) -- (2.7,2.7);
              \draw[thick] (0,2) -- (0.7,2.7);
              \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0.7,0.7) -- (2.7,0.7);
              \draw[dashed] (0.7,0.7) -- (0.7,2.7);
              \node[below] at (1,0) {$4$};
              \node[left] at (0,1) {$4$};
              \node[right] at (2.85,1.7) {$4$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <answer><p><m>V = 4^3 = 64 \text{ cm}^3</m>.</p></answer>
    </exercise>

    <remark>
      <p>This is why raising a number to the third power is called <q>cubing</q> the number: it gives the volume of a cube with that side length.</p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ============================== -->
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-rectangular-prism">
    <title>Rectangular Prism</title>

    <p>A <term>rectangular prism</term> has the shape of a box. Let's say that the length is <m>l</m>, width is <m>w</m>, and height is <m>h</m>.</p>

    <image width="40%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]
          % Front face
          \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (3,1.8) -- (0,1.8) -- cycle;
          % Back face (visible edges)
          \draw[thick] (0.9,2.5) -- (3.9,2.5) -- (3.9,0.7);
          % Connecting edges
          \draw[thick] (3,0) -- (3.9,0.7);
          \draw[thick] (3,1.8) -- (3.9,2.5);
          \draw[thick] (0,1.8) -- (0.9,2.5);
          % Hidden edges
          \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0.9,0.7) -- (3.9,0.7);
          \draw[dashed] (0.9,0.7) -- (0.9,2.5);
          % Dimension arrows
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-0.3) -- (3,-0.3) node[midway, below] {$l$};
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-0.3,0) -- (-0.3,1.8) node[midway, left] {$h$};
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (3.15,-0.15) -- (4.05,0.55) node[midway, below right] {$w$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p>Then, the volume is found by multiplying all 3 dimensions together.</p>

    <p>The volume of a rectangular prism is,</p>
    <me>\boxed{V_{\text{rect. prism}} = l \cdot w \cdot h \quad \begin{cases} l \rightarrow \text{length} \\ w \rightarrow \text{width} \\ h \rightarrow \text{height} \end{cases}}</me>

    <exercise>
      <title>Volume of a Rectangular Prism</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the volume of a rectangular prism with length 6 cm, width 4 cm, and height 3 cm.</p>
        <image width="30%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]
              % Front face
              \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (3,1.5) -- (0,1.5) -- cycle;
              % Back face edges (visible)
              \draw[thick] (0.7,2.2) -- (3.7,2.2) -- (3.7,0.7);
              \draw[thick] (3,0) -- (3.7,0.7);
              \draw[thick] (3,1.5) -- (3.7,2.2);
              \draw[thick] (0,1.5) -- (0.7,2.2);
              % Hidden edges
              \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0.7,0.7) -- (3.7,0.7);
              \draw[dashed] (0.7,0.7) -- (0.7,2.2);
              % Labels
              \node[below] at (1.5,0) {$6$};
              \node[left] at (0,0.75) {$3$};
              \node[above right] at (3.35,1.45) {$4$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <answer><p><m>V = (6)(4)(3) = 72 \text{ cm}^3</m>.</p></answer>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ============================== -->
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-volume-general-right-prism">
    <title>Volume of a General Right Prism</title>

    <p>More generally, the volume of a prism is the area of its base multiplied by its height.</p>
    <me>\boxed{V_{\text{prism}} = \text{(area of base)} \times \text{(height)}}</me>
    <p>Intuitively, a prism is a <q>stack</q> of identical cross-sections, so the volume is the area of one cross-section, multiplied by the height of the stack.</p>

    <image width="35%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
          % Shaded base (blue) - pentagonal
          \fill[blue!25] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (2.5,0.8) -- (1.2,1.3) -- (-0.2,0.8) -- cycle;
          % Base outline - visible edges
          \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (2.5,0.8);
          % Base outline - hidden edges
          \draw[thick, dashed] (2.5,0.8) -- (1.2,1.3) -- (-0.2,0.8) -- (0,0);

          % Vertical edges - visible
          \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,3.5);
          \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (2,3.5);
          \draw[thick] (2.5,0.8) -- (2.5,4.3);
          % Vertical edges - hidden
          \draw[thick, dashed] (1.2,1.3) -- (1.2,4.8);
          \draw[thick, dashed] (-0.2,0.8) -- (-0.2,4.3);

          % Horizontal slice lines (visible front portion)
          \draw[gray, dashed] (0,0.5) -- (2,0.5) -- (2.5,1.3);
          \draw[gray, dashed] (0,1.0) -- (2,1.0) -- (2.5,1.8);
          \draw[gray, dashed] (0,1.5) -- (2,1.5) -- (2.5,2.3);
          \draw[gray, dashed] (0,2.0) -- (2,2.0) -- (2.5,2.8);
          \draw[gray, dashed] (0,2.5) -- (2,2.5) -- (2.5,3.3);
          \draw[gray, dashed] (0,3.0) -- (2,3.0) -- (2.5,3.8);

          % Top face
          \draw[thick] (0,3.5) -- (2,3.5) -- (2.5,4.3) -- (1.2,4.8) -- (-0.2,4.3) -- cycle;

          % Base label
          \node at (1.1,0.5) {$B$};

          % Height arrow
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-0.7,0) -- (-0.7,3.5) node[midway, left] {$h$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p>The volume of a right prism is,</p>
    <me>\boxed{V_{\text{prism}} = Bh \quad \begin{cases} B \rightarrow \text{base area} \\ h \rightarrow \text{height} \end{cases}}</me>

    <p>This formula works for prisms with any base shape: triangular, pentagonal, hexagonal, etc. Simply compute the area of the base and multiply by the height.</p>

    <example>
      <title>Volume of a Triangular Prism</title>
      <p>Find the volume of a triangular prism whose base is a right triangle with legs 3 cm and 4 cm, and whose height is 10 cm.</p>
      <image width="25%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]
            % Bottom triangle
            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2.4,0) -- (2.4,0.9);
            \draw[dashed] (2.4,0.9) -- (0,0);
            % Top triangle
            \draw[thick] (0,3) -- (2.4,3) -- (2.4,3.9) -- cycle;
            % Vertical edges
            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,3);
            \draw[thick] (2.4,0) -- (2.4,3);
            \draw[thick] (2.4,0.9) -- (2.4,3.9);
            % Labels
            \node[below] at (1.2,0) {$4$};
            \node[right] at (2.5,0.45) {$3$};
            \node[left] at (0,1.5) {$10$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>Answer: The base is a right triangle with area <m>B = \frac{1}{2}(3)(4) = 6 \text{ cm}^2</m>. So,</p>
      <me>V = Bh = (6)(10) = 60 \text{ cm}^3.</me>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ============================== -->
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-cube-prisms">
    <title>Surface Area of a Cube and Other Prisms</title>

    <p>The surface area of a prism is found by adding the areas of all of its faces.</p>

    <p>A cube has 6 square faces which are all the same size. To see this, imagine cutting the cube along its edges and unfolding it flat. The result is called a <term>net</term>,</p>

    <image width="100%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.65]
          % --- 3D cube on the left ---
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!8] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (2,2) -- (0,2) -- cycle;
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!15] (2,0) -- (2.8,0.8) -- (2.8,2.8) -- (2,2) -- cycle;
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!5] (0,2) -- (0.8,2.8) -- (2.8,2.8) -- (2,2) -- cycle;
          \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0.8,0.8) -- (2.8,0.8);
          \draw[dashed] (0.8,0.8) -- (0.8,2.8);
          % Side length label
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-0.4) -- (2,-0.4) node[midway, below] {$x$};
          % --- Arrow ---
          \draw[-&gt;, very thick] (4,1.4) -- (5.5,1.4);
          % --- Net on the right (shifted right by 8) ---
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!8] (6,0) rectangle (8,2);
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!8] (8,0) rectangle (10,2);
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!8] (10,0) rectangle (12,2);
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!8] (12,0) rectangle (14,2);
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!8] (8,2) rectangle (10,4);
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!8] (8,-2) rectangle (10,0);
          % Count labels (small numbers in each face)
          \node at (7,1) {1};
          \node at (9,1) {2};
          \node at (11,1) {3};
          \node at (13,1) {4};
          \node at (9,3) {5};
          \node at (9,-1) {6};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p>Each of the 6 faces is a square with area <m>x^2</m>. So,</p>

    <p>The surface area of a cube is,</p>
    <me>\boxed{SA_{\text{cube}} = 6x^2 \quad x \rightarrow \text{side length}}</me>

    <example>
      <title>Volume and Surface Area of a Cube</title>
      <p>Find the volume and surface area of a cube with side length 5 cm.</p>
      <image width="35%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
            % Front face
            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (3,3) -- (0,3) -- cycle;
            % Back face
            \draw[thick] (1.2,1.2) -- (4.2,1.2) -- (4.2,4.2) -- (1.2,4.2) -- cycle;
            % Connecting edges
            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1.2,1.2);
            \draw[thick] (3,0) -- (4.2,1.2);
            \draw[thick] (3,3) -- (4.2,4.2);
            \draw[thick] (0,3) -- (1.2,4.2);
            % Labels
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-0.4) -- (3,-0.4) node[midway,below] {$5$};
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-0.4,0) -- (-0.4,3) node[midway,left] {$5$};
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (3.15,-0.15) -- (4.35,1.05) node[midway,below right] {$5$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>The volume is,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>V \amp= x^3</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 5^3</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 125 \text{ cm}^3</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>The surface area is,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>SA \amp= 6x^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 6(5)^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 6(25)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 150 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>

    <p>For a rectangular prism, it also has 6 faces, which are 3 pairs of rectangles. Unfolding it into a net, we can see all 6 faces,</p>

    <image width="100%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.65]
          % --- 3D rectangular prism on the left ---
          % Front face
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!8] (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (3,2) -- (0,2) -- cycle;
          % Right face
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!15] (3,0) -- (4,0.7) -- (4,2.7) -- (3,2) -- cycle;
          % Top face
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!5] (0,2) -- (1,2.7) -- (4,2.7) -- (3,2) -- cycle;
          % Hidden edges
          \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (1,0.7) -- (4,0.7);
          \draw[dashed] (1,0.7) -- (1,2.7);
          % Labels
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-0.4) -- (3,-0.4) node[midway, below] {$l$};
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-0.4,0) -- (-0.4,2) node[midway, left] {$h$};
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (3.1,-0.15) -- (4.1,0.55) node[midway, below right] {$w$};
          % --- Arrow ---
          \draw[-&gt;, very thick] (5.5,1.4) -- (7,1.4);
          % --- Net on the right ---
          % Bottom row: left side (wh), front (lh), right side (wh), back (lh)
          \draw[thick, fill=red!10] (8,0) rectangle (9.2,2);
          \node at (8.6,1) {\small $wh$};
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!10] (9.2,0) rectangle (12.8,2);
          \node at (11,1) {\small $lh$};
          \draw[thick, fill=red!10] (12.8,0) rectangle (14,2);
          \node at (13.4,1) {\small $wh$};
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!10] (14,0) rectangle (17.6,2);
          \node at (15.8,1) {\small $lh$};
          % Top face (lw)
          \draw[thick, fill=green!10] (9.2,2) rectangle (12.8,3.2);
          \node at (11,2.6) {\small $lw$};
          % Bottom face (lw)
          \draw[thick, fill=green!10] (9.2,-1.2) rectangle (12.8,0);
          \node at (11,-0.6) {\small $lw$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p>Then, 2 faces have area <m>lw</m>, 2 have area <m>lh</m>, and 2 have area <m>wh</m>. Adding all of these up gives the total surface area.</p>

    <p>The surface area of a rectangular prism is,</p>
    <me>\boxed{SA_{\text{rect.\ prism}} = 2lw + 2lh + 2wh \quad \begin{cases} l \rightarrow \text{length} \\ w \rightarrow \text{width} \\ h \rightarrow \text{height} \end{cases}}</me>

    <example>
      <title>Rectangular Prism</title>
      <p>A shipping box is 30 cm long, 20 cm wide, and 15 cm tall. Find its volume and surface area.</p>
      <image width="45%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
            % Front face
            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (5,2.5) -- (0,2.5) -- cycle;
            % Back face
            \draw[thick] (1.5,1.5) -- (6.5,1.5) -- (6.5,4) -- (1.5,4) -- cycle;
            % Connecting edges
            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1.5,1.5);
            \draw[thick] (5,0) -- (6.5,1.5);
            \draw[thick] (5,2.5) -- (6.5,4);
            \draw[thick] (0,2.5) -- (1.5,4);
            % Labels
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-0.4) -- (5,-0.4) node[midway,below] {$30$};
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-0.5,0) -- (-0.5,2.5) node[midway,left] {$15$};
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (5.15,-0.2) -- (6.65,1.3) node[midway,below right] {$20$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>The volume is,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>V \amp= lwh</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= (30)(20)(15)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 9000 \text{ cm}^3</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>The surface area is,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>SA \amp= 2lw + 2lh + 2wh</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 2(30)(20) + 2(30)(15) + 2(20)(15)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 1200 + 900 + 600</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 2700 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>

    <p>For a general right prism, imagine unfolding the shape.</p>

    <image width="90%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]
          % --- 3D triangular prism on the left ---
          % Fills (back to front)
          \fill[blue!10] (2.4,0) -- (1.5,0.9) -- (1.5,3.9) -- (2.4,3) -- cycle;
          \fill[blue!5] (0,0) -- (2.4,0) -- (2.4,3) -- (0,3) -- cycle;
          \fill[blue!8] (0,3) -- (2.4,3) -- (1.5,3.9) -- cycle;
          % All edges
          \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2.4,0) -- (1.5,0.9);
          \draw[dashed] (1.5,0.9) -- (0,0);
          \draw[thick] (0,3) -- (2.4,3) -- (1.5,3.9) -- cycle;
          \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,3);
          \draw[thick] (2.4,0) -- (2.4,3);
          \draw[thick] (1.5,0.9) -- (1.5,3.9);
          % Height label
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-0.5,0) -- (-0.5,3) node[midway, left] {$h$};
          % --- Arrow ---
          \draw[-&gt;, very thick] (4.5,1.2) -- (6,1.2);
          % --- Net on the right ---
          % Top base (triangle)
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!8] (7,2.4) -- (9.4,2.4) -- (8.2,3.8) -- cycle;
          \node at (8.2,2.8) {\small $B$};
          % Lateral surface (rectangle)
          \draw[thick, fill=green!10] (6.5,0) rectangle (14,2.4);
          \node at (10.25,1.2) {$P \times h$};
          % Bottom base (triangle)
          \draw[thick, fill=blue!8] (7,-1.4) -- (9.4,-1.4) -- (8.2,0) -- cycle;
          \node at (8.2,-0.6) {\small $B$};
          % Perimeter label
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (6.5,-1.8) -- (14,-1.8) node[midway, below] {$P$};
          % Height label on net
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (14.4,0) -- (14.4,2.4) node[midway, right] {$h$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p>The two bases each have area <m>B</m>. The lateral (side) surface, when unrolled flat, forms a rectangle whose width is the perimeter <m>P</m> of the base and whose height is <m>h</m>, so the area of the lateral surface is <m>Ph</m>. Adding these together gives the total surface area.</p>

    <p>The surface area of a right prism is,</p>
    <me>\boxed{SA_{\text{prism}} = 2B + Ph \quad \begin{cases} B \rightarrow \text{base area} \\ P \rightarrow \text{base perimeter} \\ h \rightarrow \text{height} \end{cases}}</me>

    <example>
      <title>Triangular Prism</title>
      <p>A right prism has a triangular base with legs 3 cm and 4 cm (a right triangle), and the prism has height 10 cm. Find its volume and surface area.</p>
      <image width="40%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
            % Front triangular face
            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (0,2.4) -- cycle;
            % Back triangular face
            \draw[thick] (1.5,1) -- (4.5,1) -- (1.5,3.4) -- cycle;
            % Connecting edges
            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1.5,1);
            \draw[thick] (3,0) -- (4.5,1);
            \draw[thick] (0,2.4) -- (1.5,3.4);
            % Labels
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-0.4) -- (3,-0.4) node[midway,below] {$3$};
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-0.4,0) -- (-0.4,2.4) node[midway,left] {$4$};
            \node at (1.8,1.7) {$5$};
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (3.2,-0.15) -- (4.7,0.85) node[midway,below right] {$10$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>First, find the base area. The base is a right triangle with legs 3 and 4, so,</p>
      <me>B = \frac{1}{2}(3)(4) = 6 \text{ cm}^2</me>
      <p>The volume is,</p>
      <me>V = Bh = 6 \times 10 = 60 \text{ cm}^3</me>
      <p>For the surface area, we need the perimeter of the base. By the Pythagorean theorem, the hypotenuse of the triangle is,</p>
      <me>c = \sqrt{3^2 + 4^2} = \sqrt{9 + 16} = \sqrt{25} = 5 \text{ cm}</me>
      <p>So the perimeter is <m>P = 3 + 4 + 5 = 12</m> cm. Then,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>SA \amp= 2B + Ph</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 2(6) + 12(10)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 12 + 120</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 132 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
  </subsection>

