  <subsection xml:id="subsec-prism-examples">
    <title>Examples</title>

    <project>
      <title>Volume and Surface Area of Prisms</title>
      <introduction><p>Find the volume and surface area of each prism.</p></introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>A cube with side length 8 cm.</p>
          <image width="25%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (3,3) -- (0,3) -- cycle;
                \draw[thick] (1,1) -- (4,1) -- (4,4) -- (1,4) -- cycle;
                \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1,1); \draw[thick] (3,0) -- (4,1);
                \draw[thick] (3,3) -- (4,4); \draw[thick] (0,3) -- (1,4);
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-0.4) -- (3,-0.4) node[midway,below] {$8$};
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </statement>
        <answer><p><m>V = 512 \text{ cm}^3</m>, <m>SA = 384 \text{ cm}^2</m>.</p></answer>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>A rectangular prism with length 12 cm, width 8 cm, and height 5 cm.</p>
          <image width="35%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.45]
                \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (5,2) -- (0,2) -- cycle;
                \draw[thick] (1.2,1) -- (6.2,1) -- (6.2,3) -- (1.2,3) -- cycle;
                \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1.2,1); \draw[thick] (5,0) -- (6.2,1);
                \draw[thick] (5,2) -- (6.2,3); \draw[thick] (0,2) -- (1.2,3);
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-0.4) -- (5,-0.4) node[midway,below] {$12$};
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-0.5,0) -- (-0.5,2) node[midway,left] {$5$};
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (5.15,-0.15) -- (6.35,0.85) node[midway,below right] {$8$};
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </statement>
        <answer><p><m>V = 480 \text{ cm}^3</m>, <m>SA = 392 \text{ cm}^2</m>.</p></answer>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement><p>A rectangular prism with dimensions <m>2.5 \text{ m} \times 3.2 \text{ m} \times 4.0 \text{ m}</m>.</p></statement>
        <answer><p><m>V = 32 \text{ m}^3</m>, <m>SA = 62.8 \text{ m}^2</m>.</p></answer>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement><p>A right prism with a triangular base. The base is an equilateral triangle with side length 6 cm, and the prism has height 14 cm.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>The area of an equilateral triangle with side <m>a</m> is <m>\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}a^2</m>.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>V = 9\sqrt{3} \times 14 = 126\sqrt{3} \approx 218.2 \text{ cm}^3</m>, <m>SA = 18\sqrt{3} + 252 \approx 283.2 \text{ cm}^2</m>.</p></answer>
      </task>
    </project>

    <project>
      <title>Reverse Problems</title>
      <introduction><p>Solve each problem.</p></introduction>

      <task>
        <statement><p>A cube has surface area <m>294 \text{ cm}^2</m>. Find its side length and volume.</p></statement>
        <hint><p><m>SA = 6x^2</m>, solve for <m>x</m>.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>x^2 = 49</m>, so <m>x = 7</m> cm. <m>V = 343 \text{ cm}^3</m>.</p></answer>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement><p>A rectangular prism has volume <m>1200 \text{ cm}^3</m>, length 15 cm, and width 10 cm. Find its height.</p></statement>
        <answer><p><m>h = \frac{1200}{15 \times 10} = 8</m> cm.</p></answer>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement><p>A cube has volume <m>1000 \text{ cm}^3</m>. Find its side length to the nearest tenth.</p></statement>
        <answer><p><m>x = \sqrt[3]{1000} = 10</m> cm.</p></answer>
      </task>
    </project>

    <project>
      <title>Unit Conversions</title>
      <introduction><p>Solve each problem.</p></introduction>

      <task>
        <statement><p>A rectangular fish tank is 60 cm long, 30 cm wide, and 40 cm tall. Find the volume of the tank in <m>\text{cm}^3</m>, then convert to litres.</p></statement>
        <answer><p><m>V = 60 \times 30 \times 40 = 72{,}000 \text{ cm}^3 = 72 \text{ L}</m>.</p></answer>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement><p>A rectangular container is <m>1.2 \text{ m} \times 0.8 \text{ m} \times 0.5 \text{ m}</m>. How many litres of water can it hold?</p></statement>
        <answer><p><m>V = 1.2 \times 0.8 \times 0.5 = 0.48 \text{ m}^3 = 480 \text{ L}</m>.</p></answer>
      </task>
    </project>

    <example>
      <title>Cube: Reverse Problem</title>
      <p>A cube has volume <m>64 \text{ cm}^3</m>. Find its side length and surface area.</p>
      <p>Since <m>V = x^3</m>, we have,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>x^3 \amp= 64</mrow>
        <mrow>x \amp= \sqrt[3]{64}</mrow>
        <mrow>x \amp= 4 \text{ cm}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>Then, the surface area is,</p>
      <me>SA = 6x^2 = 6(4)^2 = 6(16) = 96 \text{ cm}^2</me>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <title>Hexagonal Prism</title>
      <statement>
        <p>A right prism has a regular hexagonal base with side length 4 cm and height 12 cm. Find its volume.</p>
        <image width="30%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
              % Front hexagonal face
              \foreach \i in {0,...,5} {
                \draw[thick] ({2*cos(60*\i)},{2*sin(60*\i)}) -- ({2*cos(60*\i+60)},{2*sin(60*\i+60)});
              }
              % Back hexagonal face (offset)
              \foreach \i in {0,...,5} {
                \draw[thick] ({2*cos(60*\i)+1.2},{2*sin(60*\i)+0.8}) -- ({2*cos(60*\i+60)+1.2},{2*sin(60*\i+60)+0.8});
              }
              % Connecting visible edges
              \draw[thick] ({2*cos(0)},{2*sin(0)}) -- ({2*cos(0)+1.2},{2*sin(0)+0.8});
              \draw[thick] ({2*cos(60)},{2*sin(60)}) -- ({2*cos(60)+1.2},{2*sin(60)+0.8});
              \draw[thick] ({2*cos(120)},{2*sin(120)}) -- ({2*cos(120)+1.2},{2*sin(120)+0.8});
              % Label
              \node[below] at (1,-2.3) {$a = 4$};
              \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (2.6,-2) -- (3.8,-1.2) node[midway,right] {$12$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <hint><p>A regular hexagon with side length <m>a</m> has area <m>\frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}a^2</m>.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>B = \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}(4)^2 = 24\sqrt{3}</m>. <m>V = 24\sqrt{3} \times 12 = 288\sqrt{3} \approx 498.8 \text{ cm}^3</m>.</p></answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Finding Height from Surface Area</title>
      <statement><p>A closed box has a surface area of <m>126 \text{ in}^2</m>. The base of the box is 5 in by 3 in. Sketch a diagram and find the height of the box.</p></statement>
      <hint><p>Set up the SA formula and solve for <m>h</m>.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>126 = 2(15) + 2(5h) + 2(3h) = 30 + 10h + 6h = 30 + 16h</m>. So <m>16h = 96</m>, giving <m>h = 6</m> in.</p></answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Finding Width from Surface Area</title>
      <statement><p>A rectangular prism has SA <m>= 6020 \text{ cm}^2</m> and dimensions <m>34 \text{ cm} \times 20 \text{ cm} \times w</m>. Find <m>w</m>.</p></statement>
      <answer><p><m>6020 = 2(680) + 2(34w) + 2(20w) = 1360 + 68w + 40w = 1360 + 108w</m>. So <m>108w = 4660</m>, giving <m>w \approx 43.1</m> cm.</p></answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Cube with Same Volume</title>
      <statement><p>A rectangular prism has dimensions <m>9 \text{ in} \times 4 \text{ in} \times 6 \text{ in}</m>. A cube is to be made with the same volume. What is the side length of the cube?</p></statement>
      <answer><p><m>V = 9 \times 4 \times 6 = 216 \text{ in}^3</m>. <m>x^3 = 216</m>, so <m>x = 6</m> in.</p></answer>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ============================== -->
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-prism-word-problems">
    <title>Word Problems</title>

    <example>
      <title>Painting a Room</title>
      <p>A room is 5 m long, 4 m wide, and 3 m tall. How many litres of paint are needed if 1 litre covers <m>10 \text{ m}^2</m>? Assume you paint the four walls and the ceiling, but not the floor.</p>
      <image width="45%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
            % Front face
            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (5,3) -- (0,3) -- cycle;
            % Back face
            \draw[thick] (1.5,1.2) -- (6.5,1.2) -- (6.5,4.2) -- (1.5,4.2) -- cycle;
            % Connecting edges
            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1.5,1.2);
            \draw[thick] (5,0) -- (6.5,1.2);
            \draw[thick] (5,3) -- (6.5,4.2);
            \draw[thick] (0,3) -- (1.5,4.2);
            % Labels
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-0.4) -- (5,-0.4) node[midway,below] {$5$};
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-0.5,0) -- (-0.5,3) node[midway,left] {$3$};
            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (5.15,-0.15) -- (6.65,1.05) node[midway,below right] {$4$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>First, compute the area to be painted. The four walls have a combined area equal to the perimeter of the floor times the height,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>A_{\text{walls}} \amp= P \times h</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 2(5 + 4) \times 3</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 2(9)(3)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 54 \text{ m}^2</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>The ceiling has area,</p>
      <me>A_{\text{ceiling}} = 5 \times 4 = 20 \text{ m}^2</me>
      <p>The total area to paint is,</p>
      <me>A_{\text{total}} = 54 + 20 = 74 \text{ m}^2</me>
      <p>Then, the number of litres needed is,</p>
      <me>\text{litres} = \frac{74}{10} = 7.4 \text{ L}</me>
      <p>So you would need to buy at least 8 litres of paint.</p>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <title>Wrapping Paper</title>
      <statement>
        <p>A gift box is 25 cm long, 18 cm wide, and 10 cm tall. How much wrapping paper is needed to cover the box (ignoring overlap)?</p>
        <image width="35%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.45]
              \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (4.5,0) -- (4.5,1.8) -- (0,1.8) -- cycle;
              \draw[thick] (1,0.8) -- (5.5,0.8) -- (5.5,2.6) -- (1,2.6) -- cycle;
              \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1,0.8); \draw[thick] (4.5,0) -- (5.5,0.8);
              \draw[thick] (4.5,1.8) -- (5.5,2.6); \draw[thick] (0,1.8) -- (1,2.6);
              \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-0.4) -- (4.5,-0.4) node[midway,below] {$25$};
              \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-0.5,0) -- (-0.5,1.8) node[midway,left] {$10$};
              \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (4.65,-0.15) -- (5.65,0.65) node[midway,below right] {$18$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <answer><p><m>SA = 2(25)(18) + 2(25)(10) + 2(18)(10) = 900 + 500 + 360 = 1760 \text{ cm}^2</m>.</p></answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Storage Unit</title>
      <statement><p>A storage unit is 3 m long, 2.5 m wide, and 2.4 m tall. How many cubic metres of storage space does it have? How many boxes measuring <m>0.5 \text{ m} \times 0.5 \text{ m} \times 0.5 \text{ m}</m> can fit inside (assuming perfect packing)?</p></statement>
      <answer><p><m>V_{\text{unit}} = 3 \times 2.5 \times 2.4 = 18 \text{ m}^3</m>. Each box has <m>V = 0.125 \text{ m}^3</m>. Along length: <m>3/0.5 = 6</m>. Along width: <m>2.5/0.5 = 5</m>. Along height: <m>2.4/0.5 = 4</m> (with 0.4 m unused). So <m>6 \times 5 \times 4 = 120</m> boxes.</p></answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Aquarium</title>
      <statement><p>An aquarium is 80 cm long, 40 cm wide, and 50 cm tall. It is filled with water to a height of 45 cm. How many litres of water are in the aquarium?</p></statement>
      <answer><p><m>V = 80 \times 40 \times 45 = 144{,}000 \text{ cm}^3 = 144 \text{ L}</m>.</p></answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Comparing Lockers</title>
      <statement><p>At a recreation centre, you choose between two types of lockers. A single locker from a double stack measures 0.4 m wide by 0.6 m deep, and the full stack is 1.8 m tall. A single locker from a triple stack measures 30 in wide by 15 in deep, and the full stack is 41 in tall. Which type of locker gives you more space, and how much more (in cubic metres)?</p></statement>
      <hint><p>Find the height of one locker in each stack, then convert all dimensions to metres (<m>1 \text{ in} \approx 2.54 \text{ cm}</m>).</p></hint>
      <answer><p>Double-stack locker: <m>0.9 \times 0.4 \times 0.6 = 0.216 \text{ m}^3</m>. Triple-stack: height <m>= \frac{41}{3} \approx 13.67</m> in, so dimensions <m>\approx 76.2 \times 38.1 \times 34.7</m> cm. Volume <m>\approx 0.101 \text{ m}^3</m>. The double-stack gives about <m>0.12 \text{ m}^3</m> more space.</p></answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Storage Cabinet</title>
      <statement><p>A wooden storage cabinet is a right rectangular prism, 6 ft tall, 3 ft wide, and 30 in deep. Calculate the volume of the cabinet. Then, if the height is reduced by one quarter (keeping width and depth the same), what is the new volume? How does reducing one dimension by a factor of <m>k</m> affect the volume?</p></statement>
      <answer><p>Depth <m>= 30 \text{ in} = 2.5</m> ft. <m>V = 6 \times 3 \times 2.5 = 45 \text{ ft}^3</m>. New height <m>= 6 \times \frac{3}{4} = 4.5</m> ft. New <m>V = 4.5 \times 3 \times 2.5 = 33.75 \text{ ft}^3</m>. The new volume is <m>\frac{3}{4}</m> of the original. In general, multiplying one dimension by <m>k</m> multiplies the volume by <m>k</m>.</p></answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Dogsled Kennels</title>
      <statement><p>For a dogsled race, a competitor builds a trailer that is a right rectangular prism measuring 2 m wide, 1.6 m high, and 3.2 m long. The trailer is divided into 16 identical kennels (in 2 rows of 8). How much material is needed to build the kennels?</p></statement>
      <hint><p>Account for the outer walls and the interior dividing walls.</p></hint>
      <answer><p>Outer shell: <m>SA = 2(3.2)(2) + 2(3.2)(1.6) + 2(2)(1.6) = 12.8 + 10.24 + 6.4 = 29.44 \text{ m}^2</m>. Interior: one lengthwise divider <m>= 3.2 \times 1.6 = 5.12 \text{ m}^2</m>, seven crosswise dividers <m>= 7(2 \times 1.6) = 22.4 \text{ m}^2</m>. Total <m>\approx 56.96 \text{ m}^2</m>.</p></answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Maximum Volume from Material</title>
      <statement><p>You have <m>500 \text{ cm}^2</m> of material. What is the maximum volume of a cube you can make with this material?</p></statement>
      <hint><p>The SA of a cube is <m>6x^2</m>, solve for <m>x</m>.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>6x^2 = 500</m>, so <m>x = \sqrt{\frac{500}{6}} \approx 9.13</m> cm. <m>V = x^3 \approx 760.7 \text{ cm}^3</m>.</p></answer>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

